From MEMPHIS, Tenn. (UPI) Oct. 30, 1978

A hush fell over the dining room as thirty guests watched a bottle of 1864 Chateau Lafite being opened by J. Michael Broadbent, wine director of Christie’s—and the man who auctioned off the bottle that had fetched an unprecedented $18,000! Mr. Broadbent judiciously sniffed the wine—smiled broadly —and proclaimed, “Great—you’re in for a treat tonight!”’ A roar of approval went up from the crowd, and their own tastings con- firmed the glad tidings. 114 years old, and still alive, vibrant—and utterly delicious.

On these pages, we list Chateau Lafite of various vintages ranging from 1832 through 1961. None of these will cost you quite as much as $18,000—and some of them are surely at least the equal of the 1864 in terms of depth of flavor, complexity, balance and beauty. If you want one of these old, rare Lafites, we suggest ordering quickly, because in Many instances we have only one bottle.
